ce and pneumothorax risk (Kendallâ€™s (Formula presented.) âˆ’0.61; violation rate 9%), positive between vascular proximity and hemorrhage ((Formula presented.) 0.57; violations 12%), and positive between adhesions and pleural reactions ((Formula presented.) 0.49; violations 16%). Counterfactual geometric edits (Â±5â€¯mm pleural distance; Â±3â€¯mm vascular proximity) produced direction-consistent risk changes in 86 and 83% of cases, respectively. Conclusion: By translating imaging features into clinically meaningful, traceable causal frameworks, our hybrid system aligns AI logic with clinical cognition for interpretable lesion-context diagnosis and reliable downstream risk reasoning. This â€œfrom black-box to clarityâ€ shift improves trustworthiness and potential clinical utility. Copyright Â© 2025 Li, Li, Wang, Feng, Li and Liu.},
	author_keywords = {clinical causal cognition; computed tomography; interpretable diagnostics; microwave ablation; non-small cell lung cancer},
	keywords = {adult; aged; anatomical concepts; Article; bleeding; clinical outcome; cognition; computer assisted tomography; controlled study; demographics; female; human; institutional review; major clinical study; male; microwave thermotherapy; middle aged; non small cell lung cancer; pathophysiology; pleura effusion; pleura thickening; pleura tumor; pneumothorax; residual neural network; retrospective study; small cell lung cancer; thorax surgery; trustworthiness; very elderly; x-ray computed tomography},
