	abstract = {Deep learning models have achieved dermatologist-level sensitivity in melanoma detection. However, the â€œblack-boxâ€ nature of convolutional neural networks and vision transformers limits clinical trust and regulatory acceptance. Post-hoc explanation methods, such as class activation and saliency maps, have been criticized for lacking faithfulness to the underlying decision process. To address these limitations, we propose the Neuro-Symbolic Concept Bottleneck Model (NS-CBM), an intrinsically interpretable architecture that decomposes diagnosis into two stages: (1) a visual encoder that predicts clinically guided ABCDE concepts (asymmetry, border irregularity, color variegation, diameter, evolution) and (2) a differentiable logic module that reasons over these concepts to produce the final malignancy prediction. To mitigate concept leakage in standard CBMs, we introduce an orthogonality regularization term that promotes disentangled concept representations, together with a fuzzy logicâ€“based consistency regulator enabling non-linear reasoning over concept combinations. Across ISIC 2019 and 2020, NS-CBM achieves competitive diagnostic performance (AUC 0.968 Â± 0.008, mean Â± std over 5 runs) while substantially improving intervenability, enabling targeted concept correction at test time. Under the domain shift to PAD-UFES-20 and ISIC 2024, NS-CBM exhibits a reduced generalization gap (âˆ’0.081 AUC) compared to the black-box baselines (âˆ’0.159). This framework bridges the gap between high-performance neural networks and symbolic clinical reasoning, paving the way for trustworthy human-in-the-loop AI diagnostics. Â© 2026 Elsevier B.V.},
